    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-11-30T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-11-30T11:00:00-05:00" n="340"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d340">
                <head>340. Memorandum for the Record<note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d340fn0"
                        >Source: Central Intelligence Agency, Job 80 B 01285A, Box 6, McCone Files,
                        DCI Meetings with President <persName corresp="#p_JLB1">Johnson</persName>,
                        23 November-31 December 1963. Top Secret. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_MCJA1">McCone</persName> on December 2.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1963-11-30T11:00:00-05:00">November 30, 1963, 11:00 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Meeting with the President, in attendance Mr. <persName>Bundy</persName>,
                        meeting lasted approximately 1-1/2 hours</item>
                </list>
                <p>[Here follows discussion unrelated to South Asia.]</p>
                <p>6. The President then brought up the question of Pakistan and I reviewed briefly
                    the intelligence community’s feeling of concern and their view that our Pakistan
                    relationship was of the greatest importance. <persName>Bundy</persName>
                    mentioned the forthcoming December meeting between <persName corresp="#p_AKM1"
                        >Ayub</persName> and General <persName corresp="#p_TGMD1">Taylor</persName>.
                    The President made no comment but seemed to feel that <persName
                        corresp="#p_TGMD1">Taylor</persName> should remain in the United States
                    because of serious Defense budget problems. <persName>Bundy</persName> reviewed
                    the great number of commitments we have made to Pakistan and that we would come
                    to their defense if India should use our arms to attack Pakistan. The President
                    expressed the greatest of confidence in <persName corresp="#p_AKM1"
                        >Ayub</persName> and a feeling that we had not been forceful enough with
                    him, had not given him a feeling of confidence in our motives and that he had
                    drifted into the thought that we would abandon him in favor of India. He stated
                    that he wished this corrected in a most positive manner.</p>
                <p>[Here follows discussion unrelated to South Asia.]</p>
            </div>
